name: Target

comment: My trans significant other has always been able to use this restroom to change our daughter's diapers without ever being harassed or looked at negatively

name: Desert skies middle school

comment: They are for patrons but it is generally pretty busy in there so it would  be possible to slip in and use the restroom.

name: Grendel's Den

comment: You can just walk right to them. They are in the lobby so before the ticket area. If you are in the movie just remember your ticket and they’ll let you back again.

name: Lynne Garthe

comment: Family Restroom

name: Southern Utah University
comment: The University states on their website that all are able to use the gendered bathroom that they self-identify with :)

name: Geek Retreat

comment: The establishment is queer and specifically trans friendly. They have at least one trans nonbinary employee and other outwardly queer employees.

name: Elements Massage

comment: This is a massage therapy space ... for the most part the only people who go inside are clients ... but they are warm and welcoming and verified for me today that ANY BODY is welcome in their bathrooms (I did specifically ask re: trans/non-gender-conforming/non-binary ... they said ANY BODY).

name: University of Oregon

name: Thunderbird Lounge
directions: They're outside in a small building to the east of the outdoor patio.
comment: There is a shared sink area and then then gendered bathroom sections. When I called to double-check that they thought it was appropriate to add their location to this site, the bartender said, "This whole establishment is trans-friendly."

name: Pizza People Pub
directions: To the left of the bar, in back
comment: There are gendered bathrooms, but the doors to the stalls are full doors. The owner expressly said that they are trans-friendly and added, “No one’s going to be questioning anyone’s gender here.” Super nice people there!

name: Metro Cinema at the Garneau
directions: At the back of the lobby, past the theater entrance.
comment: The gendered washrooms were both transformed in gender neutral. One has stalls, the other urinals. You could ask to use them without seeing a movie.

name: Escape the Room
directions: There are two ETR locations just down the street from each other. In both the bathroom is just down the hall from the front door.
comment: It’s generally a place you’d need to have tickets to enter, but the general manager has said they would always be happy to let someone in to use the bathroom! Just ask (may need to call or knock).  I’m also submitting this in case you’re going there and are worried about needing to find a bathroom first!

name: Escape the Room
